<div class="reflist references-column-width" style="-moz-column-width: 30em; -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em; list-style-type: decimal;">
<ol class="references">
<li id="cite_note-0"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">"... modern science is a discovery as well as an invention. It was a discovery that nature generally acts regularly enough to be described by laws and even by mathematics; and required invention to devise the techniques, abstractions, apparatus, and organization for exhibiting the regularities and securing their law-like descriptions."&#160;—p.vii, <a href="/wiki/J._L._Heilbron" title="J. L. Heilbron" class="mw-redirect">J. L. Heilbron</a>, (2003, editor-in-chief) <i>The Oxford Companion to the History of Modern Science</i> New York: Oxford University Press <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0195112296" class="internal mw-magiclink-isbn">ISBN 0-19-511229-6</a></span>
