<li id="cite_note-79"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-79">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><span class="citation web"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/pubs/factsheets/medline.html">"MEDLINE Fact Sheet"</a>. Washington DC: <a href="/wiki/United_States_National_Library_of_Medicine" title="United States National Library of Medicine">United States National Library of Medicine</a><span class="printonly">. <a rel="nofollow" class="external free" href="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/pubs/factsheets/medline.html">http://www.nlm.nih.gov/pubs/factsheets/medline.html</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved 2011-10-15</span>.</span><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=MEDLINE+Fact+Sheet&amp;rft.atitle=&amp;rft.place=Washington+DC&amp;rft.pub=%5B%5BUnited+States+National+Library+of+Medicine%5D%5D&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.nlm.nih.gov%2Fpubs%2Ffactsheets%2Fmedline.html&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Science"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-80"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-80">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><span class="citation web">Petrucci, Mario. <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://writeideas.org.uk/creativescience/index.htm">"Creative Writing &lt;-&gt; Science"</a><span class="printonly">. <a rel="nofollow" class="external free" href="http://writeideas.org.uk/creativescience/index.htm">http://writeideas.org.uk/creativescience/index.htm</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved 2008-04-27</span>.</span><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=Creative+Writing+%3C-%3E+Science&amp;rft.atitle=&amp;rft.aulast=Petrucci&amp;rft.aufirst=Mario&amp;rft.au=Petrucci%2C%26%2332%3BMario&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwriteideas.org.uk%2Fcreativescience%2Findex.htm&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Science"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-81"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-81">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Women in science have included:</span>
<ul>
<li><span class="reference-text"><a href="/wiki/Hypatia" title="Hypatia">Hypatia</a> (c.350-415 CE), of the Library of Alexandria.</span></li>
<li><span class="reference-text"><a href="/wiki/Trotula" title="Trotula">Trotula</a> of Salerno, a physician c.1060 CE.</span></li>
<li><span class="reference-text"><a href="/wiki/Caroline_Herschel" title="Caroline Herschel">Caroline Herschel</a> one of the first professional astronomers of the 18th and 19th c.</span></li>
<li><span class="reference-text"><a href="/wiki/Christine_Ladd-Franklin" title="Christine Ladd-Franklin">Christine Ladd-Franklin</a>, a doctoral student of C. S. Peirce, who published Wittgenstein's proposition 5.101 in her dissertation, 40 years before Wittgenstein's publication of <a href="/wiki/Tractatus_Logico-Philosophicus" title="Tractatus Logico-Philosophicus">Tractatus Logico-Philosophicus</a>.</span></li>
<li><span class="reference-text"><a href="/wiki/Henrietta_Leavitt" title="Henrietta Leavitt" class="mw-redirect">Henrietta Leavitt</a>, a professional human computer and astronomer, who first published the significant relationship between the luminosity of <a href="/wiki/Cepheid_variable" title="Cepheid variable">Cepheid variable</a> stars and their distance from Earth. This allowed Hubble to make the discovery of the expanding universe, which led to the Big Bang theory.</span></li>
<li><span class="reference-text"><a href="/wiki/Emmy_Noether" title="Emmy Noether">Emmy Noether</a>, who proved the <a href="/wiki/Conservation_of_energy" title="Conservation of energy">conservation of energy</a> and other <a href="/wiki/Constants_of_motion" title="Constants of motion" class="mw-redirect">constants of motion</a> in 1915.</span></li>
<li><span class="reference-text"><a href="/wiki/Nina_Byers" title="Nina Byers">Nina Byers</a> notes that after 1976, women in science became much more prevalent in science, than the exceptions</span></li>
</ul>
</li>
